[[File:Khash.jpg|thumb|right|[[Armenian cuisine|Armenian]] khash]] [[File:Sheep head - Smalahove - kalleh pacheh.jpg|thumb|Fresh and prebaked sheep heads being sold in a market]] '''Khash''' ({{lang-hy|խաշ}}; {{lang-az|xaş}}; {{lang-ka|ხაში}}, Khashi), '''pacha''' ({{lang-fa|پاچه}}; {{lang-al|paçe}}; {{lang-ar|باجة}}; {{lang-bs|pače}}; {{lang-bg|пача}}; {{lang-gr| πατσάς}}), '''kalle-pache''' ({{lang-fa|کله‌پاچه}}; {{lang-tr|kelle paça}}), or '''kakaj šürpi''' ({{lang-cv|какай шÿрпи}}) refers to a dish of boiled cow or sheep parts, which might include the head, feet, and stomach ([[tripe]]). It is a traditional dish in [[Afghanistan]], [[Albania]], [[Armenia]], [[Azerbaijan]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], [[Greece]], [[Iran]], [[Iraq]], [[Mongolia]], and [[Turkey]].
== Etymology == The name ''khash'' originates from the [[Armenian language|Armenian]] verb {{transl|hy|xašel}} ({{lang|hy|խաշել}}), which means "to boil".<ref name="Adjarian">{{cite web |author=[[Hrachia Adjarian|Adjarian, Hrachia]] |url=http://www.nayiri.com/imagedDictionaryBrowser.jsp?dictionaryId=7&pageNumber=1051 |title=Armenian Etymological Dictionary |volume=2 |year=1973 |page=346 |language=hy}}</ref> The dish, initially called ''khashoy'', is mentioned by a number of medieval Armenian authors, including [[Grigor Magistros]] (11th century), [[Mkhitar Heratsi]] (12th century), and Yesayi Nchetsi (13th century).<ref name="Adjarian"/>
The [[Persian language|Persian]] term {{transl|fa|pāče}} literally means "trotter".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vajehyab.com/amid/پاچه |title=پاچه |trans-title=pāče |language=fa |work=Amid Dictionary |access-date=April 24, 2018}}</ref> The combination of a sheep's head and trotters is called {{transl|fa|kalle-pāče}}, which literally means "head [and] trotter" in Persian.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vajehyab.com/amid/کله+پاچه |title=کله پاچه |trans-title=kalle pāče |language=fa |work=Amid Dictionary |access-date=April 24, 2018}}</ref>
== In the Caucasus == [[File:Azerbaijani khash.jpg|thumb|[[Azerbaijani cuisine|Azerbaijani]] khash]] Khash is a purist meal with great parsimony in ingredients. The feet are depilated, cleaned, kept in cold water in order to get rid of bad smell, and boiled in water all night long, until the water has become a thick broth and the meat has separated from the bones.{{cn |date=April 2018}} No salt or spices are added during the boiling process. The dish is served hot. One may add [[salt]], [[garlic]], [[lemon]] juice, or [[vinegar]] according to one's taste. Dried [[lavash]] is often crumbled into the broth to add substance.{{cn |date=April 2018}} Khash is generally served with a variety of other foods, such as hot [[bell pepper|green and yellow pepper]]s, [[pickling|pickle]]s, [[radish]]es, [[cheese]], and fresh [[leaf vegetable|greens]] such as [[garden cress|cress]]. The meal is almost always accompanied by [[vodka]] (preferably [[morus (plant)|mulberry]] vodka) and [[mineral water]].{{cn |date=April 2018}}
In Georgia, Khashi is served together with onions, milk, salt and [[Chacha (brandy)|chacha]]. Usually they eat this dish early morning, or during hangovers.
In the medieval Armenian medical textbook ''[[Relief of Fevers]]'' (1184), khash was described as a dish with healing properties, e.g., against snuffle. It was recommended to eat it while drinking wine.<ref>{{cite book |author=[[Mkhitar Heratsi|Heratsi, Mkhitar]] |title=Relief of Fevers |url=http://titus.fkidg1.uni-frankfurt.de/texte/etcs/arm/heraci/herac.htm |chapter=Chapter 6}}</ref> In case of ailment, khash from the legs of yeanling was advised.<ref>{{cite book |author=[[Mkhitar Heratsi|Heratsi, Mkhitar]] |title=Relief of Fevers |url=http://titus.fkidg1.uni-frankfurt.de/texte/etcs/arm/heraci/herac.htm |chapter=Chapter 10}}</ref>
Formerly a nutritious winter food, it is now considered a delicacy, and is enjoyed as a festive winter meal. Modern-day convention in [[Armenia]] dictates that it should be consumed during the month that has an ''r'' in its name, thus excluding May, June, July, and August (''[[month]] names in [[Armenian language|Armenian]] are derivatives of the [[Latin]] names''). Khash is traditionally consumed during cold months in [[Azerbaijan]] and [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].{{cn |date=April 2018}}
In the [[list of dishes from the Caucasus|Caucasus]], khash is often seen as a food to be consumed in the mornings after a party, as it is known to battle hangovers (especially by men) and eaten with a "[[hair of the dog]]" vodka chaser.<ref>{{cite book |last=Elliott |first=Mark |title=Azerbaijan with Excursions to Georgia |publisher=Trailblazer |year=2010 |page=356 |isbn=978-1-905864-23-2}}</ref>
There is much [[ritual]] involved in khash parties. Many participants abstain from eating the previous evening, and insist upon using only their hands to consume the unusual (and often unwieldy) meal. Because of the potency and strong smell of the meal, and because it is eaten early in the mornings and so often enjoyed in conjunction with alcohol, khash is usually served on the weekend or on [[holiday]]s.{{cn |date=April 2018}}
== In Iran and Afghanistan == {{multiple image |align=right |total_width=300 |image1=Khash 1.jpg |caption1=Kalle-pache ({{transl|fa|kalle-pāče}}) in Tehran |image2=Iranian pache dish.jpg |caption2=An Iranian pache ({{transl|fa|pāče}}) dish }} Kalle-pache ({{transl|fa|kalle-pāče}}; {{transl|prs|kalla-pāča}}; literally meaning "head [and] trotter") consists of a sheep's head ([[Offal#Middle East and North Africa|including the brain]]) and trotters,<ref>{{cite book |last=Edelstein |first=Sari |title=Food, Cuisine, and Cultural Competency for Culinary, Hospitality, and Nutrition Professionals |publisher=Jones & Bartlett Learning |year=2009 |page=236 |isbn=0-7637-5965-1}}</ref><ref name=king>{{cite book |last=King |first= Bart |title=The Big Book of Gross Stuff |publisher=Gibbs Smith |year=2010 |page=243 |isbn=1-4236-0746-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/03/13/sheep-heads-brains-and-ho_n_174650.html |title=Sheep Heads, Brains And Hooves Are Delicacies In Iran |work=HuffPost |date=April 13, 2009 |access-date=January 8, 2016}}</ref> and is typically seasoned with [[lemon]] and [[cinnamon]].<ref name="king"/> Usually consumed as a breakfast soup,<ref name="king"/> kalle-pache is traditional to Afghanistan<ref>{{cite book |last=Elliott |first=Mark |title=Azerbaijan with Excursions to Georgia |publisher=Trailblazer |year=2010 |page=353 |isbn=978-1-905864-23-2}}</ref> and [[Iran]].<ref name="king"/>
In Iran, kalle-pache is usually cooked in specialty stores, and is served in the morning.<ref name="Iranica">{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/kalla-paca-a-traditional-dish |title=KALLA-PĀČA |encyclopedia=Encyclopædia Iranica |date=April 20, 2012 |volume=XV |page=408}}</ref> It is especially consumed during cold seasons.<ref name="Iranica"/> To prepare kalle-pache, the sheep's head and trotters are collected, cooked, and treated as per the recipe.<ref>{{cite book |last=Field |first=Henry |title=Contributions to the anthropology of Iran |volume=2 |publisher=Chicago Natural History Museum |year=1939 |page=559}}</ref>
== In Israel == During winter it is very common to eat sheep or cow parts soup with onions and spices, especially the legs which is called 'Maraq rigl' it is usually accompanied with an alcoholic drink.
== In Arab countries == Pacha is a traditional [[Iraqi cuisine|Iraqi]] dish made from sheep's head, trotters, and stomach; all boiled slowly and served with bread sunken in the broth.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foodbycountry.com/Germany-to-Japan/Iraq.html |title=Food in Iraq – Iraqi Cuisine – popular, dishes, diet, common meals, customs |publisher=Foodbycountry.com |date=April 6, 2001 |access-date=March 14, 2010}}</ref> The cheeks and tongues are considered the best parts. Many people prefer not to eat the eyeballs which could be removed before cooking.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.christiansofiraq.com/petrus8285.html |title=Assyrian Restuarant (Sic) in Chicago Reminds Iraqis of Home |publisher=Christiansofiraq.com |date=August 28, 2005 |accessdate=March 14, 2010}}</ref> The stomach lining would be filled with rice and lamb and stitched with a sewing thread ({{lang-ar|كيبايات}}).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chowhound.chow.com/topics/113967 |title=Little Shedrak's Pacha (Lamb's Head) – Chicago Area – Chowhound |publisher=Chowhound.chow.com |access-date=March 14, 2010}}</ref> Sheep brain is also included.<ref name="Finkel2009">{{cite book |author=David Finkel |title=The Good Soldiers |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BtNheyB7b_sC&pg=PT55&lpg=PT55&dq=sheep+brains+iraq&source=bl&ots=yv72cNLZZu&sig=-VH9Q40TEKJR1M97bpKqfAbu3Ok&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjf3djzzZnKAhXCHB4KHeIxCYMQ6AEIKTAC#v=onepage&q=sheep%20brains%20iraq&f=false |date=September 15, 2009 |publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux |isbn=978-1-4299-5271-2 |page=55}}</ref><ref name="Martinkus2004">{{cite book |author=John Martinkus |title=Travels in American Iraq |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ieCTk1wq8ngC&pg=PA29&lpg=PA29&dq=sheep+brains+iraq&source=bl&ots=9QRnFe6J3A&sig=QMDunSI7ss-OQ5AnlOvgJU1swxU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjf3djzzZnKAhXCHB4KHeIxCYMQ6AEILDAD#v=onepage&q=sheep%20brains%20iraq&f=false |year=2004 |publisher=Black Inc. |isbn=978-1-86395-285-9 |page=29}}</ref><ref name="Gish2015">{{cite book |author=Peggy Faw Gish |title=Iraq |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hVSnBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA212&lpg=PA212&dq=sheep+brains+iraq&source=bl&ots=VjzJnis46T&sig=UakbDGVDIsUgcBa0YHAGhXhoq9w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjf3djzzZnKAhXCHB4KHeIxCYMQ6AEIRDAJ#v=onepage&q=sheep%20brains%20iraq&f=false |date=February 12, 2015 |publisher=Wipf and Stock Publishers |isbn=978-1-4982-1763-7 |page=212}}</ref>
The dish is known in [[Kuwait]], [[Bahrain]], and other [[Persian Gulf]] countries as ''pacha'' ({{lang|ar|پاچة}}), too. A variation of that is found in other Arab countries such as in [[Egypt]] and is known as ''kawari''' ({{lang|ar|كوارع}}), Egyptians eat cow brain and sheep brain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://egyptian-cuisine-recipes.com/recipes/meat |title=Meat &#124; Egyptian Cuisine and Recipes |website=Egyptian-cuisine-recipes.com |access-date=January 8, 2016}}</ref>
== In Albania == [[Albania]]'s popular pache ({{lang|sq|paçe}}) consists of a sheep's or any cattle's head, that is boiled until meat comes off easily. It is then stewed with garlic, onion, black pepper, and vinegar. Sometimes a little flour is added to thicken the stew. It makes a hot and hearty winter stew.{{cn |date=April 2018}}
== In Turkey == In [[Turkish cuisine|Turkish culinary culture]], ''pacha'' ({{lang|tr|paça}} is a generic word for certain soup preparations, especially with offal, but also without it. In most parts of [[Turkey]], such as in [[Kastamonu Province|Kastamonu]], for instance, the term {{lang|tr|ayak paça}} ("feet pacha") is used for cow, sheep, or goat hooves,<ref name="Koz2002">{{cite book |author=Koz, M. Sabri |title=Yemek kitabı: tarih, halkbilimi, edebiyat |language=tr |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d_uBAAAAMAAJ |year=2002 |publisher=Kitabevi |page=486 |isbn=978-975-7321-74-3}}</ref> and the term {{lang|tr|kelle paça}} is used for "head pacha" ([[chorba]]). Sometimes the term {{lang|tr|dil paça}} is also used for [[beef tongue|tongue]] soup, while "meat pacha" is made with {{lang|tr|gerdan}} ([[scrag end]] of sheep's neck).{{cn |date=April 2018}} In Turkey, the word {{lang|tr|kelle}} refers to a sheep's head roasted in the oven, which is served after grilling at specialized offal restaurants.{{cn |date=April 2018}}
== In Greece == [[File:Patsas_soup_200509.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Patsas_soup_200509.jpg|thumb|245x245px|A bowl of Greek patsás (with ''skordostoubi'' and hot pepper flakes)]] The [[Greek cuisine|Greek]] version, called ''patsás'' (πατσάς), may be seasoned with red wine vinegar and garlic (''skordostoubi''), or thickened with [[Avgolemono|avgolémono]]. The Greek version sometimes uses calf feet with the tripe.
Specialized [[Taverna|tavernas]] serving patsa are known as ''patsatzidika''. Because patsas has the reputation of remedying hang-over and aiding digestion, ''patsatzidika'' are often working overnight, serving people returning home after [[dinner]] or [[Clubbing (subculture)|clubbing]].
== Similar dishes == * [[Paya (food)|Paya]], South Asian version of this dish * [[Smalahove]], boiled sheep's head, a traditional western [[Norwegian cuisine|Norwegian]] food * [[Soğuk paça]], a Turkish cold dish made with the [[Gelatin|jelly]] obtained from sheep or cow hooves * [[Svið]], an [[Icelandic cuisine|Icelandic]] dish that includes a sheep's head cut in half
